%F A142983 a(n) = n!*p(n+1)*sum {k = 1..n} (-1)^(k+1)/(p(k)*p(k+1)), where p(n) = n. Recurrence: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2, a(n+2) = 2*a(n+1)+(n+1)*(n+2)*a(n). The sequence b(n):= n!*p(n+1) satisfies the same recurrence with b(1) = 2, b(2) = 6. Hence we obtain the finite continued fraction expansion a(n)/b(n) = 1/(2 +1*2/(2 +2*3/(2 +3*4/(2 +...+(n-1)*n/2)))), for n >=2. The behavior of a(n) for large n is given by lim n -> infinity a(n)/b(n) = 1/(2 +1*2/(2 +2*3/(2 +3*4/(2 +...+n*(n+1)/(2 +...))))) = sum {k = 1..inf} (-1)^(k+1)/(k*(k+1)) = 2*log(2) - 1;
%F A142983 E.g.f.: (2*log(x+1)-x)/(x-1)^2. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 21 2012
